<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1494,2022]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,404,1494,1518]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
Antennae ciliated. Forewing pattern includes uniform ground colour of yellow or orange tinge, a sub-basal and a discocellular black spot present. In male genitalia, the uncus with two sub-basal, dorso-lateral horn-like small processes is unique for this group. Valva is undivided, without any process, and ending in a sharp apex; costa more or less s-shaped. Tegumen is very broad and attached to vinculum, with a small stalk. Transtilla apex is conspicuously bulbous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="146" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1494,2022]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,154,394]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="146" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1674,1698]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Externally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta" authorityYear="2019" box="[447,628,1674,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Parvuspina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tawaghatensis">
<emphasis box="[447,628,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">P. tawaghatensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[643,746,1674,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,214,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[166,1422,177,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6: Adults. 1, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand, Tawaghat (NZCZSI); 2, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar (NZCZSI); 3, M. calamaria, holotype ♀, N India, Himachal Pradesh (©NHM); 4, M. dasara, type ♂, Java (©NHM); 5, M. undulata, type ♂, E India, Meghalaya (©NHM); 6, Planovalvata confusa, ♂, India, Arunachal Pradesh, Hunli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484334/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
) resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[877,1127,1674,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calamaria">
<emphasis box="[877,1127,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Miltochrista calamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1142,1207,1674,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,214,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[166,1422,177,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6: Adults. 1, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand, Tawaghat (NZCZSI); 2, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar (NZCZSI); 3, M. calamaria, holotype ♀, N India, Himachal Pradesh (©NHM); 4, M. dasara, type ♂, Java (©NHM); 5, M. undulata, type ♂, E India, Meghalaya (©NHM); 6, Planovalvata confusa, ♂, India, Arunachal Pradesh, Hunli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484334/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[1230,1340,1674,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lyclene" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dasara">
<emphasis box="[1230,1340,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">M. dasara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1356,1423,1674,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,214,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[166,1422,177,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6: Adults. 1, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand, Tawaghat (NZCZSI); 2, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar (NZCZSI); 3, M. calamaria, holotype ♀, N India, Himachal Pradesh (©NHM); 4, M. dasara, type ♂, Java (©NHM); 5, M. undulata, type ♂, E India, Meghalaya (©NHM); 6, Planovalvata confusa, ♂, India, Arunachal Pradesh, Hunli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484334/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName box="[197,329,1710,1734]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lyclene" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulata">
<emphasis box="[197,329,1710,1734]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">M. undulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[344,409,1710,1734]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,214,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[166,1422,177,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6: Adults. 1, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand, Tawaghat (NZCZSI); 2, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar (NZCZSI); 3, M. calamaria, holotype ♀, N India, Himachal Pradesh (©NHM); 4, M. dasara, type ♂, Java (©NHM); 5, M. undulata, type ♂, E India, Meghalaya (©NHM); 6, Planovalvata confusa, ♂, India, Arunachal Pradesh, Hunli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484334/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) but its forewings are comparatively broader. In male genitalia, all the above mentioned 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Miltochrista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<figureCitation box="[323,451,1746,1770]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–12" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[241,1351,176,1856]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1364,167,1874]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 10–12: Male genitalia. 7, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand, Tawaghat; 8, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar; 9, holotype &amp; paratype dorsal view; 10, M. calamaria, E India, Assam (©NHM); 11, M. dasara, type ♂, Java (©NHM); 12, M. undulata, S Vietnam (©NHM).." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484338/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Figs. 10–12</figureCitation>
) are considerably distinct from 
<emphasis box="[790,913,1747,1770]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Parvuspina</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[928,1029,1746,1770]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[151,1381,179,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1399,167,1957]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9: Male genitalia. 7, P. tawaghatensis, sp. nov., holotype ♂, India, Uttarakhand,Tawaghat; 8, P.tawaghatensis, sp. nov., paratype ♂, India, Himachal Pradesh, Joginder Nagar; 9, holotype &amp; paratype dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484336" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484336/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Figs. 7–9</figureCitation>
) due to their simple, long, narrow and curved uncus; valva divided into distal costal and distal saccular process; tegumen long and narrow; and transtilla apex simple. On the basis of external male genitalia, the new genus is closely similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dubatolov &amp; Kishida" authorityName="Dubatolov &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2012" box="[1054,1436,1818,1842]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Planovalvata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1054,1196,1818,1842]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Planovalvata</emphasis>
Dubatolov &amp; Kishida
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,235,1854,1878]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="5.[151,244,758,780]" captionTargetBox="[162,1345,187,711]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1354,185,719]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 13: Male genitalia. 13, P. confusa, ♂, India, Arunachal Pradesh, Hunli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3484340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3484340/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) and an African genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Wallengren" authorityName="Wallengren. In" authorityYear="1863" box="[480,694,1854,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Tumicla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[480,566,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Tumicla</emphasis>
Wallengren
</taxonomicName>
(treated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Volynkin, A. V. &amp; Laszlo, G. M." box="[814,1079,1854,1878]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="293 - 306" refId="ref2265" refString="Volynkin, A. V. &amp; Laszlo, G. M. (2018) On the taxonomy of the genus Tumicla Wallengren, 1863 with description of two new species from Mozambique (Lepidoptera: Erebidae: Arctiinae). Zootaxa, 4442 (2), 293 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4442.2.6" type="journal article" year="2018">Volynkin &amp; László 2018</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<emphasis box="[1205,1328,1855,1878]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Parvuspina</emphasis>
is distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2012" box="[210,352,1890,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Planovalvata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[210,352,1890,1914]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Planovalvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to absence of longitudinal zone of costally directed strong setae at the entire distal section of the valva, an important character present in the valva of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2012" box="[711,853,1926,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Planovalvata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[711,853,1926,1950]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Planovalvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Furthermore, in 
<emphasis box="[1040,1163,1927,1950]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Parvuspina</emphasis>
the tegumen is extraordinary broad, the distal part of costal margin of valva is smooth and transtilla apices are noticeably bulbous whereas, in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Planovalvata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Planovalvata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
tegumen is extremely narrow, distal part of costal margin of valva is irregularly dentate and transtilla apices are simple. The new genus is distinct from its other closely similar African genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Wallengren" authorityName="Wallengren. In" authorityYear="1863" box="[991,1206,154,178]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Tumicla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[991,1077,154,178]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Tumicla</emphasis>
Wallengren
</taxonomicName>
by the uncus curved, apically pointed, having two sub-basal, dorso-lateral horn like small processes which are absent in apically spatulated uncus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wallengren. In" authorityName="Wallengren. In" authorityYear="1863" box="[249,499,226,250]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Tumicla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[249,335,226,250]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Tumicla</emphasis>
Wallengren. In
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[505,628,226,249]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Parvuspina</emphasis>
, valva apex is acute, strongly and smoothly bent upwards and costa is more or less s-shaped whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wallengren. In" authorityYear="1863" box="[446,532,262,286]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Tumicla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,532,262,286]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Tumicla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, valva apex is slightly bent outwards and downwards; apex of costal margin strongly tapered and bearing irregular, short dentation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,154,394]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,334,358]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the genus is due to small spines on the base of the uncus and derived from two latin words: Parvus – the small and spinae – the spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
